{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at a module handoff boundary (HTTP handler -> signature verifier -> enqueue path). A unit test of only the HMAC function would miss regressions where the handler still forwards on auth failure. No real OS/network/model dependency is required.","test_description":"Wire the real handler with real signature-validation middleware/module and a spy/fake queue adapter. Send an in-process HTTP request with mismatched body/signature. Assert 401 and assert enqueue/forwarding was never called.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"An event is written to the persistent queue before the HTTP 200 acknowledgment is returned to the sender.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is ordering across modules (handler response lifecycle vs queue persistence call). Needs real wiring between handler and queue implementation interface, but not real OS/network/subprocess. Rejected System because behavior text does not require real external queue infrastructure, only ordering guarantee.","test_description":"Use handler + queue module in-process. Instrument queue write completion (promise resolution/hook) and response send time. Assert write completes before 200 is emitted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The handler returns the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing of the event to finish.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Bug appears when handler, queue, and downstream worker orchestration interact. Unit logic alone can miss accidental await/blocking. No real OS/network/model dependency is required.","test_description":"Connect handler to queue and a downstream processor stub that blocks for a long duration. Send request and assert response is returned before processor completion while event is still queued/processing asynchronously.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even when downstream processing of earlier events is slow and concurrent.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is an end-to-end latency SLO under concurrency and backpressure. Real wall-clock scheduling, server runtime behavior, and concurrent request handling can invalidate in-process fakes/timers. Mocking can hide event-loop starvation/thread-pool contention issues.","test_description":"Run the real service process, generate concurrent traffic with earlier events forcing slow downstream work, and measure actual HTTP latency for new webhook requests. Assert p95 (or strict per-test bound) response time stays under 3s.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"An event whose ID was already received is not written to the queue a second time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Deduplication is a state handoff/data consistency behavior between handler and queue persistence layer (or uniqueness index). Unit tests of ID-check helpers can miss duplicate writes caused by wiring/transaction bugs. No real OS/network/model dependency required by behavior text.","test_description":"Use real handler + real local persistence-backed queue module. Submit the same event ID twice and assert exactly one persisted queue record/enqueue side effect.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"When the queue reports it is full, the handler returns 503 with a Retry-After header.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This verifies mapping of a queue-capacity failure signal to HTTP semantics across module boundaries (queue adapter -> handler response). A pure unit test of status-code constants is insufficient. Rejected higher levels: no requirement for real network/OS or model output.","test_description":"Wire handler to queue module (or contract-faithful fake) that returns a deterministic 'full' error. Send request and assert HTTP 503 plus Retry-After header value/presence.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit and rejects events that would exceed it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Target is queue component correctness with real persistence wiring/config, best caught by exercising the real queue implementation against local storage. Mock queue would always pass and hide real enforcement bugs. Rejected System because behavior text does not require external networked queue/subprocess; local DB/filesystem-backed integration is sufficient.","test_description":"Instantiate the real persistent queue with a small capacity config using local storage backend. Fill to capacity, then push one more event and assert rejection/error and unchanged persisted count.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
